ODE IX.

ΤΟ LOLLIUS.

N EVER deem they must perish, the verses, which I, Who was born where the waters of Aufidus roar, To the chords of the lyre with a cunning ally Unknown to the bards of my country before!

Though Maeonian Homer unrivalled may reign, Yet are not the Muses Pindaric unknown,

The threats of Alcaeus, the Ceian's sad strain, And stately Stesichorus' lordlier tone.

Unforgot is the sportive Anacreon's lay,

Stin, still sighs the passion, unquenched is the fire, Which the Lesbian maiden, in days far away,

From her love-laden bosom breathed into the lyre.
